of reactive oxygen species in the extracellular space","Binding of antibodies to microbial surfaces"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Erecognition, engulfment, and degradation of particles\u003C/strong\u003E. Phagocytosis is a sequential process that involves three main steps: (1) recognition and attachment of the particle to the phagocyte via specific receptors, (2) engulfment of the particle with formation of a phagosome, and (3) killing and degradation of the ingested material after fusion of the phagosome with lysosomes to form a phagolysosome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMigration of phagocytes to sites of inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes chemotaxis, which precedes phagocytosis but is a separate process.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect destruction of microbes by release of lysosomal enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - While phagocytes can release lysosomal contents extracellularly, this is not phagocytosis itself but rather a separate process called degranulation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of reactive oxygen species in the extracellular space\u003C/strong\u003E - This is one mechanism of microbial killing, but it occurs primarily within the phagolysosome during phagocytosis rather than defining the process itself.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinding of antibodies to microbial surfaces\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes opsonization, which enhances phagocytosis but is not phagocytosis itself. Opsonins like IgG antibodies coat microbes to facilitate their recognition by phagocyte receptors.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhagocytosis is facilitated by various receptors on phagocytes, including mannose receptors that bind terminal mannose and fucose residues on microbial surfaces, scavenger receptors that recognize various microbes, and receptors for opsonins such as IgG and complement component C3b. The efficiency of phagocytosis is greatly enhanced when microbes are coated with these opsonins.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Phagocytosis involves three sequential steps: recognition and attachment, engulfment with phagosome formation, and killing/degradation of the ingested material.","Phagocytes recognize microbes through receptors including mannose receptors, scavenger receptors, and receptors for opsonins.","Opsonins such as IgG antibodies, C3b, and plasma lectins enhance phagocytosis by coating microbes for recognition by specific phagocyte receptors."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 80-81"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77265"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20642"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77265"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-23T13:02:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T13:03:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13518"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94165"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10955"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Acute inflammation","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:38+10:30","u